const QB=[
{id:1,text:"Which of the following is an example of why testing is necessary?",options:["Dynamic testing increases quality by causing test objects to fail in ways that could never be achieved by the users","Static testing is used by developers to identify failures in their program code earlier than can be achieved through dynamic testing","Static analysis provides evidence to customers that the elements of the system that provide no outputs are fit for release","Reviews increase the quality of requirements specifications and lead to fewer changes being needed in derived work products"],correct:[3],explanation:"Reviews are a form of static testing applied early in the SDLC to find defects in requirements. Removing these defects early prevents wasted effort on derived work products (design, code) that would be based on faulty requirements."},
{id:2,text:"Which of the following statements about quality assurance (QA) and/or quality control (QC) is correct?",options:["QA is performed as part of testing","Testing is performed as part of QC","Testing is another term for QC","Testing is performed as part of QA"],correct:[1],explanation:"QC aims to achieve appropriate quality levels by identifying and correcting product defects. Testing is a significant part of QC and helps uncover these defects. QA, by contrast, focuses on process improvement using a preventive approach."},
{id:3,text:"One of the 'principles of testing' states that exhaustive testing is impossible. Which of the following is an example of addressing this principle in practice?",options:["Creating test cases that cover every possible specified output","Documenting all possible test input variations and prioritizing these based on importance","Starting testing as early as possible with reviews and other static testing approaches","Using equivalence partitioning and boundary value analysis to generate test cases"],correct:[3],explanation:"EP and BVA are techniques that address exhaustive testing being impossible by systematically reducing the number of test cases needed."},
{id:4,text:"Which test activity involves working with test data requirements, test conditions, test environment requirements and test cases?",options:["Test design","Test execution","Test analysis","Test implementation"],correct:[0],explanation:"Test design works with test conditions (from analysis) to create test cases, and identifies test data and environment requirements."},
{id:5,text:"Which of the following is MOST likely to impact how testing is performed for a given test object?",options:["The average level of experience of the organization's marketing team","The knowledge of users that a new system is being developed for them","The number of years' experience of the members of the test team","The end user's organizational structure for a commercial music streaming application"],correct:[2],explanation:"The experience of the test team directly impacts how testing is performed."},
{id:6,text:"Which of the following statements is a CORRECT example of the value of traceability?",options:["Traceability between the mitigated risks and passing test cases provides a means of determining the level of residual risk","Traceability between user requirements and test execution results provides a means of measuring project progress against business goals","Traceability between testers and failing test cases provides a means of determining the skill level of the testers","Traceability between the identified risks and written test conditions provides a means of determining which risks are worth testing"],correct:[1],explanation:"Traceability between user requirements and test execution results shows which requirements have been tested, providing a means of measuring project progress against business goals."},
{id:7,text:"Which of the following is MOST likely to be an example of a tester using a generic skill when testing?",options:["The tester's deep knowledge of computer games meant they got on well with a developer who was also into gaming","The tester was a former pilot and was better able to understand the acceptance criteria for the helicopter control system","The tester previously worked as a programmer and used their skills to better communicate with the business analysts","The tester was very careful not to make mistakes when they methodically generated test cases prior to starting exploratory testing"],correct:[1],explanation:"Domain knowledge that helps understand and communicate with end-users and business representatives is a key generic skill for testers. A tester with piloting experience would better appreciate the acceptance criteria for a helicopter control system."},
{id:8,text:"Which of the following is an advantage of the whole-team approach?",options:["It allows team members to take on any role at any time","It only needs a single team to support the complete development project","It embeds business representatives alongside developers in the same team","It generates a team synergy that benefits the entire project"],correct:[3],explanation:"The whole-team approach generates synergy that benefits the entire project through shared responsibility for quality."},
{id:9,text:"Which of the following statements about the chosen software development lifecycle is CORRECT?",options:["If agile software development is used, system test automation replaces the need for regression testing","If a sequential development model is used, then the dynamic testing is typically restricted to later in the lifecycle","If an iterative development model is used, then component testing is typically performed manually by developers","If an incremental development model is used, then static testing is done in early increments and dynamic testing in later increments"],correct:[1],explanation:"In sequential models, dynamic testing (requiring executable code) happens later since code is produced in later phases."},
{id:10,text:"Which of the following is a good testing practice that applies to all software development lifecycles?",options:["Testers should review work products as part of the next development phase","Testers should review work products as soon as drafts are available","Testers should review work products before test analysis and design begins","Testers should review work products immediately after they are published"],correct:[1],explanation:"Reviewing work products as soon as drafts are available ensures early defect detection across all SDLCs."},
{id:11,text:"Which of the following is an example of a test-first approach to development?",options:["Test-Driven Development","Coverage-Driven Development","Quality-Driven Development","Feature-Driven Development"],correct:[0],explanation:"TDD is the classic test-first approach where tests are written before the code."},
{id:12,text:"Which of the following statements about DevOps is CORRECT?",options:["To speed up releases, continuous integration encourages developers to submit code quickly without completing component testing","To be able to update and release systems more frequently, many automated regression tests are required to reduce regression danger","To treat developers and operations equally, testers allocate more effort to release testing using a shift-right approach","To create increased synergy, the testing must become fully automated with no manual testing"],correct:[1],explanation:"Frequent releases in DevOps require extensive automated regression testing to catch regressions early."},
{id:13,text:"Which of the following is MOST likely to be performed as part of system testing?",options:["Security testing of a credit management system by an independent test team","Testing the interface of a currency exchange system with an external banking system","Beta testing of a remote learning system by courseware developers","Testing interactions between the user interface and database of a human resources system"],correct:[0],explanation:"Security testing of a complete system by an independent team is characteristic of system testing."},
{id:14,text:"Which of the following statements is CORRECT?",options:["Regression tests increase as the project progresses, whereas confirmation tests decrease","Regression tests are created when the test object is fixed, whereas confirmation tests run when enhanced","Regression testing checks the operational environment remains unchanged, whereas confirmation testing tests changes","Regression testing checks for adverse effects in unchanged code, whereas confirmation testing tests changed code"],correct:[3],explanation:"Regression testing looks for side effects in unchanged areas; confirmation testing verifies the fix works."},
{id:15,text:"Which of the following is an example of a defect that can be found by static testing but NOT by dynamic testing?",options:["Lack of usability provided through the user interface","Code with no path that reaches it","Poor response times for most of the expected users","Required features that are not implemented in the code"],correct:[1],explanation:"Unreachable code (dead code) can only be found by static analysis, not by running the program since the code never executes."},
{id:16,text:"Which of the following is a benefit of early and frequent stakeholder feedback?",options:["Managers are aware of which developers are less productive","It allows project managers to prioritize their stakeholder interactions","It facilitates early communication of potential quality issues","End users better understand why the delivery is delayed"],correct:[2],explanation:"Early and frequent feedback facilitates early communication of potential quality issues."},
{id:17,text:"Given the following task descriptions:\n\n1. The quality characteristics to be evaluated and the exit criteria are selected\n2. Everyone has access to the work product\n3. Anomalies are identified in the work product\n4. Anomalies are discussed\n\nAnd the following review activities:\nA. Individual review\nB. Review initiation\nC. Planning\nD. Communication and analysis\n\nWhich BEST matches the task descriptions and activities?",options:["1B, 2C, 3D, 4A","1B, 2D, 3C, 4A","1C, 2A, 3B, 4D","1C, 2B, 3A, 4D"],correct:[3],explanation:"Planning selects quality characteristics (1C), initiation distributes the work product (2B), individual review finds anomalies (3A), communication discusses them (4D)."},
{id:18,text:"Given the following roles in reviews:\n1. Scribe\n2. Review leader\n3. Facilitator\n4. Manager\n\nAnd the following responsibilities:\nA. Ensures effective running of review meetings and safe environment\nB. Records review information such as decisions and anomalies\nC. Decides what is to be reviewed and provides resources\nD. Takes overall responsibility for the review, organizing when and where\n\nWhich BEST matches the roles and responsibilities?",options:["1A, 2B, 3D, 4C","1A, 2C, 3B, 4D","1B, 2D, 3A, 4C","1B, 2D, 3C, 4A"],correct:[2],explanation:"Scribe records info (1B), review leader takes overall responsibility (2D), facilitator ensures effective meetings (3A), manager decides and provides resources (4C)."},
{id:19,text:"Which of the following statements BEST describes the difference between decision table testing and branch testing?",options:["In decision table testing, test cases are derived from decision statements in the code. In branch testing, from knowledge of the control flow.","In decision table testing, test cases are derived from the specification describing business logic. In branch testing, from anticipation of potential defects.","In decision table testing, test cases are derived from knowledge of the control flow. In branch testing, from the specification.","In decision table testing, test cases are independent of implementation. In branch testing, test cases can only be created after design or implementation of the code."],correct:[3],explanation:"Decision table testing is a black-box technique (implementation-independent), while branch testing is a white-box technique requiring knowledge of the code."},
{id:20,text:"Customers of the TestWash car wash chain have cards recording the number of washes. The initial value is 0. After entering, the system increases it by one.\n\nFor every 10th wash: 10% discount. For every 20th wash: additional 40% discount (50% total).\n\nWhich set of input data (current wash numbers) achieves the highest equivalence partition coverage?",options:["19, 20, 30","11, 12, 20","1, 10, 50","10, 29, 30, 31"],correct:[0],explanation:"There are 3 valid equivalence partitions: no discount, 50% discount (every 20th wash), and 10% discount (every 10th wash). The set {19, 20, 30} covers all three: 19 → no discount, 20 → 50% discount, 30 → 10% discount."},
{id:21,text:"You are testing a form that verifies password length. Correct length: 6–12 characters inclusive. Otherwise incorrect.\n\nAt first, the form is empty (length = 0). You apply BVA to the 'password length' variable.\n\nYour test cases achieve 100% 2-value BVA coverage. The team wants to add tests for 100% 3-value BVA coverage.\n\nWhich additional password lengths should be tested?",options:["4, 5, 13, 14","7, 11","1, 5, 13","1, 4, 7, 11, 14"],correct:[3],explanation:"Three equivalence partitions: too short {0–5}, OK {6–12}, too long {13+}. 2-value BVA already covers: 0, 5, 6, 12, 13. 3-value BVA requires: 0, 1, 4, 5, 6, 7, 11, 12, 13, 14. Additional lengths needed: 1, 4, 7, 11, and 14."},
{id:22,text:"The following decision table contains the rules for determining the risk of atherosclerosis.",html:qB22Html,textAfterHtml:"What is the decision table coverage achieved by these test cases?",options:["40%","60%","80%","100%"],correct:[1],explanation:"There are 5 rules (columns) in the decision table. TC1 and TC2 both cover Rule 4, TC3 and TC4 both cover Rule 2, and TC5 covers Rule 5. So 3 out of 5 rules are covered: (3/5)×100% = 60%."},
{id:23,text:"A storage system can store up to three elements and is modeled by the following state transition diagram. The variable N represents the number of currently stored elements.",html:qB23Svg,textAfterHtml:"Which of the following test cases, represented as sequences of events, achieves the highest level of valid transitions coverage?",options:["Add, Remove, Add, Add, Add","Add, Add, Add, Add, Remove, Remove","Add, Add, Add, Remove, Remove","Add, Add, Add, Remove, Add"],correct:[2],explanation:"There are 5 valid transitions: E1(START→NOT FULL), E2(NOT FULL→NOT FULL, Add), E3(NOT FULL→NOT FULL, Remove), E4(NOT FULL→FULL), E5(FULL→NOT FULL). Option c) Add,Add,Add,Remove,Remove covers E1,E2,E4,E5,E3 — all 5 transitions for 100% coverage."},
{id:24,text:"You run two test cases, T1 and T2, on the same code. Test T1 achieved 40% statement coverage and test T2 achieved 65% statement coverage.\n\nWhich of the following sentences must be necessarily true?",options:["The test suite composed with T1 and T2 achieves 105% statement coverage","There exists at least one statement that must have been executed by both T1 and T2","At least 5% of the statements in the code under test are non-executable","The test suite composed of T1 and T2 achieves full branch coverage"],correct:[1],explanation:"Since 40% + 65% = 105% > 100%, at least 5% of statements must have been covered by both tests. So at least one statement was executed by both."},
{id:25,text:"Let the branch coverage metric be defined as BCov = (X / Y) * 100%.\n\nWhat do X and Y represent in this formula?",options:["X = number of decision outcomes exercised by test cases\nY = total number of decision outcomes in the code","X = number of conditional branches exercised by test cases\nY = total number of branches in the code","X = number of branches exercised by test cases\nY = total number of branches in the code","X = number of conditional branches exercised by test cases\nY = total number of decision outcomes in the code"],correct:[2],explanation:"Branch coverage is measured as the number of branches exercised by the test cases divided by the total number of branches, expressed as a percentage. Branches include both conditional and unconditional transfers of control."},
{id:26,text:"Which TWO of the following statements provide the BEST rationale for using exploratory testing?\n\na) Testers have not been allocated enough time for test design and test execution\nb) The existing test strategy requires that testers use formal, black-box test techniques\nc) The specification is written in a formal language that can be processed by a tool\nd) Testers are the members of an agile team and have good programming skills\ne) Testers are experienced in the business domain and have good analytical skills",options:["a and e","b and d","c and e","a and d"],correct:[0],explanation:"Exploratory testing is best when time is limited (a) and testers have strong domain knowledge and analytical skills (e)."},
{id:27,text:"Which of the following BEST fits as an element of the checklist used in checklist-based testing?",options:['"The developer made an error when implementing the code"','"The achieved statement coverage exceeds 85%"','"The program works correctly regarding functional and non-functional requirements"','"The error messages are written in language that the user can understand"'],correct:[3],explanation:"Checklist items should be specific, verifiable conditions. Error message readability is a concrete testable item."},
{id:28,text:'Consider the following acceptance criteria for a user story:\n\nGiven that the user is logged in and on the homepage,\nWhen the user clicks on the "Add Item" button,\nThen the "Create Item" form should appear,\nAnd the user should be able to input a name and price for the new item.\n\nIn what format is this acceptance criteria written?',options:["Rule-oriented","Scenario-oriented","Product-oriented","Process-oriented"],correct:[1],explanation:"The Given/When/Then format is a scenario-oriented format for writing acceptance criteria."},
{id:29,text:'Your team analyzes the following user story:\n\n"As a registered customer, I want to be able to view my previous orders on the company\'s website, so that I can keep track of my purchases."\n\nWhich of the following test cases will NOT be relevant for this user story?',options:["Input: customer logs in and clicks 'see order history' → Expected: system shows list of previous orders with date, order number, total cost","Input: customer clicks on an order from the order list → Expected: system displays individual items with prices and quantities","Input: customer clicks 'Sort ascending' on order history → Expected: system shows orders sorted by order number ascending","Input: unregistered customer registers with valid email not in database → Expected: system accepts registration and creates account"],correct:[3],explanation:"Registering a new customer is not relevant to the user story about viewing previous orders."},
{id:30,text:"Your team follows a DevOps delivery pipeline. The first three steps are:\n\n(1) Code development\n(2) Submit code into version control and merge into the 'test' branch\n(3) Perform component testing for the submitted code\n\nWhich is BEST suited as the entry criterion for step (2)?",options:["Static analysis returns no high severity warnings for the submitted code","System version control reports no conflicts when merging code into the 'test' branch","Component tests are compiled and ready to be executed","Statement coverage is at least 80%"],correct:[0],explanation:"Static analysis with no high-severity warnings is a good entry criterion before submitting code to version control."},
{id:31,text:"You want to estimate the test effort for a new project using estimation based on ratios. You calculate the test-to-development effort ratio using averaged data from four historical projects.",html:qB31Html,textAfterHtml:"What is your estimate of the test effort in this project?",options:["$40,000","$80,000","$81,250","$82,500"],correct:[1],explanation:"Average dev effort = (800K+1200K+600K+1000K)/4 = 900K. Average test effort = (40K+130K+70K+120K)/4 = 90K. Ratio = 90K/900K = 0.1. New project: 800K × 0.1 = $80,000."},
{id:32,text:"You are testing a web application with SEARCH, VIEW, ADD to cart, and ORDER functions.\n\nTest cases with priorities:\n• TC1: SEARCH product A (medium)\n• TC2: VIEW product A details (low)\n• TC3: ADD product B to cart (medium)\n• TC4: ADD product C to cart (high)\n• TC5: place an ORDER (high)\n\nDependencies:\n• SEARCH before VIEW\n• VIEW before ADD\n• ADD before ORDER\n\nWhich test case should be executed fourth?",options:["TC3","TC1","TC2","TC4"],correct:[0],explanation:"Following dependencies: SEARCH→VIEW→ADD→ORDER. Within each group, order by priority (smaller = higher). TC1 (SEARCH) first, TC2 (VIEW) second, TC4 (ADD, high priority) third, TC3 (ADD, medium priority) fourth, TC5 (ORDER) fifth. So TC3 is the fourth test case executed."},
{id:33,text:'According to the testing quadrants model, which of the following falls into quadrant Q1 ("technology facing" and "support the team")?',options:["Usability testing","Functional testing","User acceptance testing","Component integration testing"],correct:[3],explanation:"Q1 is technology facing, supporting the team — this includes component testing and component integration testing."},
{id:34,text:"Given the following risks:\n1. Ineffective loop implementation causes long system responses\n2. Consumers change their preferences\n3. Flooding of the server room\n4. Patients above a certain age receive inaccurate reports\n\nAnd mitigation activities:\nA. Risk acceptance\nB. Performance testing\nC. Using boundary value analysis\nD. Risk transfer\n\nWhich BEST matches the risks with mitigation activities?",options:["1C, 2D, 3A, 4B","1B, 2D, 3A, 4C","1B, 2A, 3D, 4C","1C, 2A, 3D, 4B"],correct:[2],explanation:"Loop causing slow responses→Performance testing (1B). Consumer preference changes→Accept the risk (2A). Flooding→Transfer via insurance (3D). Age-based inaccuracy→BVA for boundary testing (4C)."},
{id:35,text:"Which of the following is a product quality metric?",options:["Mean time to failure","Number of defects found","Requirements coverage","Defect detection percentage"],correct:[0],explanation:"Mean time to failure (MTTF) is a product quality metric measuring reliability of the product itself."},
{id:36,text:"You are a member of a test team in North America, developing a product for a client in Europe. The team is agile with DevOps and CI/CD pipeline.\n\nWhich is the LEAST effective way to communicate test progress to the customer?",options:["Face-to-face","Dashboards","Email","Video conferencing"],correct:[0],explanation:"Face-to-face communication is least effective when the team and client are on different continents (North America vs Europe)."},
{id:37,text:"Which of the following BEST describes an example of how configuration management (CM) supports testing?",options:["Having the version number of the environment, the CM tool can retrieve the version numbers of libraries, stubs and drivers used","Having a record of test input values, the CM tool can execute test cases and calculate coverage","Having data about the date of purchase of a software license, the CM tool generates license expiry info","Having the version number of a test case, the CM tool can automatically generate test data"],correct:[0],explanation:"CM tracks environment versions and can retrieve related component versions — this directly supports testing by ensuring reproducible environments."},
{id:38,text:"You are testing a sort function that gets a set of numbers and returns them sorted in ascending order. The log from test execution looks as follows:",html:qB38Html,textAfterHtml:"Which provides the BEST description of the failure for a defect report?",options:["The system fails to sort several sets of numbers. Reference: TC3, TC4, TC5.","The system seems to disregard duplicates while sorting. Reference: TC3, TC4, TC5.","The system fails to sort negative numbers. Reference: TC4, TC5.","TC3, TC4 and TC5 have defects (duplicate input data) and should be corrected."],correct:[1],explanation:"Looking at the failures: TC3 input has duplicate 7, output drops one. TC4 has duplicate -2 and -3, output drops them. TC5 has duplicate 0 and 4, output drops them. The pattern is duplicates being removed."},
{id:39,text:"Given the following descriptions:\n1. Support workflow tracking\n2. Facilitate communication\n3. Virtual machines\n4. Support reviews\n\nAnd the following test tool categories:\nA. Static testing tools\nB. Tools supporting scalability and deployment standardization\nC. DevOps tools\nD. Collaboration tools\n\nWhich BEST matches the descriptions and categories?",options:["1A, 2B, 3C, 4D","1B, 2D, 3C, 4A","1C, 2D, 3B, 4A","1D, 2C, 3A, 4B"],correct:[2],explanation:"Workflow tracking→DevOps tools (1C), Communication→Collaboration tools (2D), Virtual machines→Scalability tools (3B), Reviews→Static testing tools (4A)."},
{id:40,text:"Which of the following is MOST likely to be a benefit of test automation?",options:["It provides coverage measures that are too complicated for humans to derive","It shares responsibility for the testing with the tool vendor","It removes the need for critical thinking when analyzing test results","It generates test cases from an analysis of the program code"],correct:[0],explanation:"Test automation tools can calculate complex coverage metrics (like branch coverage, condition coverage) that would be impractical to track manually."}
];


const QC=[
{id:1,text:"Which of the following is a typical test objective?",options:["Validating that documented requirements are met","Causing failures and identifying defects","Initiating errors and identifying root causes","Verifying the test object meets user expectations"],correct:[1],explanation:"Causing failures and identifying defects is the most common objective of dynamic testing."},
{id:2,text:"Which of the following statements BEST describes the difference between testing and debugging?",options:["Testing causes failures while debugging fixes failures","Testing is a negative activity while debugging is a positive activity","Testing determines that defects exist while debugging removes defects","Testing finds the cause of defects while debugging fixes the cause of defects"],correct:[2],explanation:"Testing determines that defects exist (directly through static testing or indirectly through failures in dynamic testing). Debugging is performed by developers to locate and fix defects."},
{id:3,text:"The 'absence-of-defects fallacy' is one of the principles of testing. Which of the following is an example of addressing this principle in practice?",options:["Explaining that it is not possible for testing to show the absence of defects","Supporting the end users to perform acceptance testing","Ensuring that no implementation defects remain in the delivered system","Modifying tests that cause no failures to ensure few defects remain"],correct:[1],explanation:"Supporting end users to perform acceptance testing helps validate that the system meets users' needs and expectations, addressing the absence-of-defects fallacy."},
{id:4,text:"Which of the following test activities are MOST likely to involve the application of boundary value analysis and equivalence partitioning?\n\na) Test implementation\nb) Test design\nc) Test execution\nd) Test monitoring\ne) Test analysis",options:["a and c","b and e","c and d","a and d"],correct:[1],explanation:"Test techniques like BVA and EP are used during test analysis (to identify test conditions) and test design (to create test cases from those conditions)."},
{id:5,text:"Given the following testware:\n1. Coverage items\n2. Change requests\n3. Test execution schedule\n4. Prioritized test conditions\n\nAnd the following test activities:\nA. Test analysis\nB. Test design\nC. Test implementation\nD. Test completion\n\nWhich BEST shows the testware produced by the activities?",options:["1B, 2D, 3C, 4A","1B, 2D, 3A, 4C","1D, 2C, 3A, 4B","1D, 2C, 3B, 4A"],correct:[0],explanation:"Coverage items come from test design (1B), change requests from test completion (2D), test execution schedule from test implementation (3C), and prioritized test conditions from test analysis (4A)."},
{id:6,text:"Which of the following statements about the different testing roles is MOST likely to be CORRECT?",options:["In Agile, the test management role is the team's responsibility, while testing is primarily done by a single individual from outside the team","The testing role is primarily responsible for test monitoring and control, while test management is responsible for test planning and completion","In Agile, test management activities spanning multiple teams are handled by a test manager outside the team, while some tasks are handled by the team itself","The test management role is primarily responsible for test analysis and design, while testing is primarily responsible for implementation and execution"],correct:[2],explanation:"In Agile, the team handles some test management tasks internally, but cross-team test management activities are handled by a test manager outside the development team."},
{id:7,text:"Which of the following is an advantage of the whole-team approach?",options:["Teams with no testers","Improved team dynamics","Specialist team members","Larger team sizes"],correct:[1],explanation:"The whole-team approach fosters superior team dynamics through diverse skill sets, robust communication, and collaboration that benefits the entire project."},
{id:8,text:"Which of the following statements about the independence of testing is CORRECT?",options:["Independent testers will find defects due to their different technical perspective from developers, but their independence may lead to an adversarial relationship with the developers","Developers' familiarity with their own code means they only find a few defects in it, however their shared software background with testers means these defects would also be found by the testers","Independent testing requires testers who are outside the developer's team and ideally from outside the organization, however these testers find it difficult to understand the application domain","Testers from outside the developer's team are more independent than testers from within the team, but the testers from within the team are more likely to be blamed for delays in product release"],correct:[0],explanation:"Independent testers find different types of defects due to varied backgrounds and perspectives, but this independence may lead to communication problems and an adversarial relationship."},
{id:9,text:"Which of the following is a good testing practice that applies to all software development lifecycles?",options:["For each test level, there is a corresponding development level","For each test objective, there is a corresponding development objective","For every software test activity, there is a corresponding user activity","For every software development activity, there is a corresponding test activity"],correct:[3],explanation:"Quality control applies to all development activities, meaning every software development activity has a corresponding test activity."},
{id:10,text:"Which of the following is an example of a test-first approach to development?",options:["Component Test-Driven Development","Integration Test-Driven Development","System Test-Driven Development","Acceptance Test-Driven Development"],correct:[3],explanation:"Acceptance Test-Driven Development (ATDD) is a well-known example of a test-first approach to development."},
{id:11,text:"Which of the following provides the BEST description of the shift-left approach?",options:["When agreed by the developers, manual activities on the left-hand side of the test process are automated to support early testing","Where cost-effective, test activities are moved to be performed earlier in the SDLC to reduce the total cost of quality by reducing defects found later","When they have spare time, testers automate tests for regression testing, starting with component tests","When available, testers are trained to perform tasks early in the SDLC to allow more test activities to be automated later"],correct:[1],explanation:"Shift-left emphasizes starting testing earlier in the SDLC. While it requires additional effort early on, the overall savings from finding defects earlier are higher."},
{id:12,text:"Which of the following is LEAST likely to occur as a result of a retrospective?",options:["The quality of future test objects improves by identifying improvements in development practices","Test efficiency improves by speeding up the configuration of test environments through automation","End users' understanding of the development and test processes is improved","Automated test scripts are enhanced through feedback from developers"],correct:[2],explanation:"End users rarely participate in or receive reports from retrospectives, so improving their understanding of development processes is the least likely outcome."},
{id:13,text:"Which of the following test levels is MOST likely being performed if the testing is focused on validation and is not being performed by testers?",options:["Component testing","Component integration testing","System integration testing","Acceptance testing"],correct:[3],explanation:"Acceptance testing focuses on validation (meeting user needs) and is ideally performed by end users, not testers."},
{id:14,text:"The navigation system software has been updated due to it suggesting routes that break traffic laws. Which of the following BEST describes the testing that will be performed?",options:["Only confirmation testing","Confirmation testing then regression testing","Only regression testing","Regression testing then confirmation testing"],correct:[1],explanation:"First, confirmation testing verifies the fix works correctly. Then regression testing ensures no defects were introduced in unchanged areas. Confirmation testing precedes regression testing."},
{id:15,text:"Given the following example defects:\n\ni. Two different parts of the design specification disagree due to complexity\nii. A response time is too long and makes users lose patience\niii. A path in the code cannot be reached during execution\niv. A variable is declared but never subsequently used in the program\nv. The amount of memory needed by the program to generate a report is too high\n\nWhich BEST identifies defects that could be found by static testing (rather than dynamic testing)?",options:["ii, v","iii, v","i, ii, iv","i, iii, iv"],correct:[3],explanation:"Static testing finds: (i) specification inconsistencies, (iii) unreachable code, and (iv) unused variables. Response time (ii) and memory usage (v) require dynamic testing."},
{id:16,text:"Which of the following is a benefit of early and frequent stakeholder feedback?",options:["Changes to requirements are understood and implemented earlier","It ensures business stakeholders understand user requirements","It allows product owners to change their requirements as often as they want","End users are told which requirements will not be implemented prior to release"],correct:[0],explanation:"Early and frequent feedback ensures that changes in stakeholder requirements are understood and implemented sooner, preventing misunderstandings."},
{id:17,text:"Given the following review types:\n1. Technical review\n2. Informal review\n3. Inspection\n4. Walkthrough\n\nAnd descriptions:\nA. Includes objectives such as gaining consensus, generating new ideas, and motivating authors to improve\nB. Includes objectives such as educating reviewers, gaining consensus, generating new ideas and detecting potential defects\nC. Main objective is detecting potential defects and requires metrics collection for process improvement\nD. Main objective is detecting potential defects and generates no formal documented output\n\nWhich BEST matches the review types and descriptions?",options:["1A, 2B, 3C, 4D","1A, 2D, 3C, 4B","1B, 2C, 3D, 4A","1C, 2D, 3A, 4B"],correct:[1],explanation:"Technical review: consensus & new ideas (1A). Informal review: detects defects, no formal output (2D). Inspection: detects defects with metrics (3C). Walkthrough: educates reviewers, consensus, new ideas (4B)."},
{id:18,text:"Which of the following is a factor that contributes to a successful review?",options:["Ensure management participate as reviewers","Split large work products into smaller parts","Set reviewer evaluation as an objective","Plan to cover one document per review"],correct:[1],explanation:"Breaking work products into small enough parts prevents reviewers from losing focus during individual review or review meetings."},
{id:19,text:"What is the MAIN difference between black-box test techniques and experience-based test techniques?",options:["The test object","The test level at which the test technique is used","The test basis","The software development lifecycle (SDLC) in which the test technique can be used"],correct:[2],explanation:"Black-box techniques use specifications as the test basis. Experience-based techniques use the tester's knowledge and experience, and may not use the specification at all."},
{id:20,text:"You are testing a PIN validator. A PIN is valid if it consists of four digits, at least two of which are different.\n\nEquivalence partitions:\n\u2022 PIN length: \"length correct\" (4 digits) and \"length incorrect\" (not 4 digits)\n\u2022 Different digits: \"correct\" (at least 2 different) and \"incorrect\" (all same)\n\nWhich is a MINIMUM set of input test data that covers all identified equivalence partitions?",options:["1234, 12345, 1","111, 1111, 1112","1, 1234","12345, 1234"],correct:[2],explanation:"Value '1' covers 'length incorrect' and 'all digits same'. Value '1234' covers 'length correct' and 'at least 2 different digits'. These two values cover all four partitions."},
{id:21,text:"A developer implements this business rule:\n\nIF (value \u2264 100 OR value \u2265 200) THEN write \"value incorrect\"\nELSE write \"value OK\"\n\nYou design test cases using 2-value BVA.\nWhich set of test inputs achieves the greatest coverage?",options:["100, 150, 200, 201","99, 100, 200, 201","98, 99, 100, 101","101, 150, 199, 200"],correct:[3],explanation:"The boundary values for 2-value BVA are 100, 101, 199, and 200. Set d) covers 101, 199, and 200 = 3 out of 4 boundary values (75%), which is the greatest coverage among the options."},
{id:22,text:"You are designing test cases based on this decision table for driving test results.",html:qC22Html,textAfterHtml:"What test data will show that there are contradictory rules in the decision table?",options:["C1=T, C2=T, C3=F","C1=T, C2=F, C3=T","C1=T, C2=T, C3=T and C1=F, C2=T, C3=T","C1=F, C2=F, C3=F"],correct:[3],explanation:"The combination (F, F, F) matches both R2 (C2=F, with C1 and C3 as don't-care) and R3 (C1=F, C3=F, with C2 as don't-care), but R2 and R3 have different actions, showing a contradiction."},
{id:23,text:"You are designing test cases based on the following state transition diagram for a hotel room booking system.",html:qC23Svg,textAfterHtml:"What is the MINIMUM number of test cases required to achieve 100% valid transitions coverage?",options:["3","2","5","6"],correct:[0],explanation:"Three test cases are needed: TC1: START→REQUESTING→CONFIRMED→END, TC2: START→REQUESTING→WAITING LIST→CONFIRMED→END, TC3: START→REQUESTING→WAITING LIST→END. These cover all 6 valid transitions."},
{id:24,text:"You want to apply branch testing to the code represented by the following control flow graph.",html:qC24Svg,textAfterHtml:"How many coverage items do you need to test?",options:["2","4","8","7"],correct:[2],explanation:"In branch testing, coverage items are branches (edges in the control flow graph). There are 8 edges in this graph, so 8 coverage items."},
{id:25,text:"How can white-box testing be useful in support of black-box testing?",options:["White-box coverage measures can help testers evaluate black-box tests in terms of the code coverage achieved by these black-box tests","White-box coverage analysis can help testers identify unreachable fragments of the source code","Branch testing subsumes black-box test techniques, so achieving full branch coverage guarantees full coverage of any black-box technique","White-box test techniques can provide coverage items for black-box techniques"],correct:[0],explanation:"White-box coverage measures provide an objective measurement of how much code is exercised by black-box tests, allowing testers to identify gaps and generate additional tests."},
{id:26,text:"Consider the following list:\n\n\u2022 Correct input not accepted\n\u2022 Incorrect input accepted\n\u2022 Wrong output format\n\u2022 Division by zero\n\nWhat test technique is MOST PROBABLY used by the tester who uses this list?",options:["Exploratory testing","Fault attack","Checklist-based testing","Boundary value analysis"],correct:[1],explanation:"This is a list of possible failures/errors. Fault attacks (a methodical approach to error guessing) require the tester to create a list of possible errors, defects and failures, and design tests to expose them."},
{id:27,text:"Which of the following BEST describes how using checklist-based testing can result in increased coverage?",options:["Checklist items can be defined at a sufficiently low level of detail, so the tester can implement and execute detailed test cases","Checklists can be automated, so each time an automated test execution covers the checklist items, it results in additional coverage","Each checklist item should be tested separately and independently, so the elements cover different areas","Two testers designing and executing tests based on the same high-level checklist items will typically perform the testing in slightly different ways"],correct:[3],explanation:"High-level checklist items allow variability in testing. When two testers follow the same checklist, each may use different test data and steps, resulting in greater combined coverage."},
{id:28,text:"Which of the following provides the BEST example of a scenario-oriented acceptance criterion?",options:["The application must allow users to delete their account and all associated data upon request","When a customer adds an item to their cart and proceeds to checkout, they should be prompted to log in or create an account if they haven't already done so","IF (contain(product(23).Name, cart.products())) THEN return FALSE","The website must comply with the ICT Accessibility 508 Standards and ensure that all content is accessible to users with disabilities"],correct:[1],explanation:"This describes an example scenario the system must support (add to cart → checkout → login prompt), which is characteristic of scenario-oriented acceptance criteria."},
{id:29,text:"You are using acceptance test-driven development and designing test cases based on the following user story:",html:qC29Html,textAfterHtml:"Which test case is the MOST reasonable one to test AC3?",options:["Check that a Regular user can access floors 1 and 3","Check that a Regular user cannot access floor 4","Check that a Special user can access floor 5","Check that a Special user can access floors 1, 2 and 3"],correct:[3],explanation:"AC3 states Special users have all Regular user access rights. Testing that a Special user can access floors 1, 2, and 3 (the Regular user floors) directly verifies this."},
{id:30,text:"Which of the following is NOT a purpose of a test plan?",options:["To define test data and expected results for component tests and component integration tests","To define as exit criteria that '100% statement coverage and 100% branch coverage must be achieved'","To describe what fields the test progress report shall contain and its format","To explain why system integration testing will be excluded from testing, although the test strategy requires it"],correct:[0],explanation:"A test plan may include test data requirements as part of the approach, but not the detailed test data and expected results for individual test cases. That level of detail belongs in the test cases themselves."},
{id:31,text:"At the beginning of each iteration, the team estimates the work (in person-days) using the formula E(n) = (3\u00d7A(n\u22121) + A(n\u22122)) / 4.",html:qC31Html,textAfterHtml:"What is the estimated amount of work for iteration #5?",options:["10.5 person-days","8.25 person-days","6.5 person-days","9.4 person-days"],correct:[2],explanation:"From the chart: A(4)=6, A(3)=8. E(5) = (3\u00d76 + 8) / 4 = (18+8) / 4 = 26/4 = 6.5 person-days."},
{id:32,text:"You are preparing a test execution schedule for seven test cases (TC 1 to TC 7) with priorities (1=highest) and dependencies shown below.",html:qC32Svg,textAfterHtml:"Which test case should be executed sixth?",options:["TC 3","TC 5","TC 6","TC 2"],correct:[0],explanation:"Respecting dependencies and priorities: TC4→TC7 (priority 1), then TC1→TC2→TC5 (priority 1), then TC3 (priority 2), then TC6 (priority 3). Full order: TC4, TC7, TC1, TC2, TC5, TC3, TC6. Sixth is TC3."},
{id:33,text:"What does the test pyramid model show?",options:["That tests may have different priorities","That tests may have different granularity","That tests may require different coverage criteria","That tests may depend on other tests"],correct:[1],explanation:"The test pyramid model shows that tests have different levels of granularity, with many low-level tests (unit) at the base and fewer high-level tests (UI/E2E) at the top."},
{id:34,text:"What is the relationship between the testing quadrants, test levels and test types?",options:["Testing quadrants represent particular combinations of test levels and test types, defining their location in the SDLC","Testing quadrants describe the degree of granularity of individual test types performed at each test level","Testing quadrants assign the test types that can be performed to the test levels","Testing quadrants group test levels and test types by several criteria such as targeting specific stakeholders"],correct:[3],explanation:"Testing quadrants group test levels, test types, activities, and techniques by criteria: business facing vs. technology facing, and supporting the team vs. critiquing the product."},
{id:35,text:"Which of the following is an example of how product risk analysis may influence the thoroughness and scope of testing?",options:["Continuous risk monitoring allows us to identify emerging risk as soon as possible","Risk identification allows us to implement risk mitigation activities and reduce the risk level","The assessed risk level helps us to select the rigor of testing","Risk analysis allows us to derive coverage items"],correct:[2],explanation:"The assessed risk level directly influences how thoroughly and rigorously testing is performed — higher risks get more rigorous testing."},
{id:36,text:"Which of the following activities in the test process makes the MOST use of test progress reports?",options:["Test design","Test completion","Test analysis","Test planning"],correct:[1],explanation:"A test completion report is prepared during test completion using information from test progress reports and other data."},
{id:37,text:"Which of the following is NOT an example of how configuration management supports testing?",options:["All commits to the repository are uniquely identified and version controlled","All changes in the test environment elements are tracked","All requirement specifications are referenced unambiguously in test plans","All identified defects have an assigned status"],correct:[3],explanation:"Defect status tracking is part of defect management, not configuration management. CM deals with version control, environment tracking, and unambiguous referencing of items."},
{id:38,text:"Consider the following defect report for a web-based shopping application:",html:qC38Html,textAfterHtml:"What is the MOST important information that is missing from this report?",options:["Name of the tester and date of the report","Test environment elements and their version numbers","Identification of the test object","Impact on the interests of stakeholders"],correct:[1],explanation:"The browser and device information are missing. This is critical because the login button issue could be browser- or device-specific, and this information helps developers reproduce the problem."},
{id:39,text:"Tools from which of the following categories help with the organization of test cases, detected defects and configuration management?",options:["Test execution and coverage tools","Test design and implementation tools","Defect management tools","Test management tools"],correct:[3],explanation:"Test management tools facilitate the management of the SDLC, requirements, tests, defects, and configuration management — covering all three areas mentioned."},
{id:40,text:"Which of the following is MOST likely to be a benefit of test automation?",options:["The capability of generating test cases without access to the test basis","The achievement of increased coverage through more objective assessment","The increase in test execution times available with higher processing power","The prevention of human errors through greater consistency and repeatability"],correct:[3],explanation:"Test automation prevents human errors through consistent, repeatable execution — tests are derived systematically, data is created uniformly, and tests run in the same order every time."}
];



